Identify {= company =}+ companies as public providers or operators of warehouse robotics or fulfillment automation products as of {= target_as_of_date =}; for each company, identify {= public_automation_case =}+ discrete public automation cases. For each (`company`, `case_name`) case, cover each `evidence_side` listed below with a role-specific public source (i.e. {= url =}+ URL) exposing a focused case-scoped finding.

The task studies public market structure around warehouse automation through concrete cases: customer deployments, productized capability launches, integrations, strategic relationships, acquisitions/transactions, financing/listing events tied to automation delivery, or other public capability cases. A company-wide product page can help, but the submitted unit must be a discrete public case under the company rather than a generic vendor profile. Each case should be strong enough to support a company-side claim, an external deployment/counterparty anchor, operational or software substance, and independent outcome/scale validation; a vendor case study with no independent result, scale, or live-status validation is not enough.

The `case_name` should be a concrete identifier, not a broad product category. Prefer a name that includes a customer/operator/counterparty, site/facility/region, product launch/version, transaction/event, and/or source-stated year when available. Examples of good case identities include "DHL Supply Chain 2021 expanded Locus deployment", "Decathlon Skyfleet European warehouse rollout", or "AutoStore-Kardex global partner-network addition". Weak case identities like "AMR product page", "warehouse robotics capability", "customer success", or "automation software" should fail unless the page itself states a discrete public launch/event with anchors.

Evidence sides:
{=% for evidence_side, description in evidence_sides.items() =%}
- `{= evidence_side =}`: {= description =}
{=% endfor =%}

The cited page should be fully public, accessible, and usable as a normal page. The company or business unit ought to sell, operate, or publicly offer a warehouse robotics, goods-to-person, AMR, AS/RS, robotic picking, palletizing, sortation, automated storage, warehouse execution/orchestration, or materially adjacent fulfillment automation product. Generic WMS/software vendors, logistics providers, market-report publishers, consultancies, integrators with no automation product or solution surface, and robotics research labs without commercial warehouse automation claims are outside scope; logistics-provider identities count only when the page is about their own automation product or business unit rather than their use of another vendor's automation.

Requirements:
- The page must clearly identify the claimed company or business unit.
- The page must identify the claimed public automation case at the submitted `evidence_side` bar: company-side update/capability case, external deployment/counterparty anchor, operational/software substance, or independent outcome/scale validation for the same case.
- The page must tie the claim to warehouse robotics, fulfillment automation, warehouse execution/orchestration, or a closely adjacent warehouse automation context.
- The page must make the case identity concrete. At least one of customer/operator/counterparty, site/facility/region, launch/product version, event/transaction, or event year must be visible from the page content or URL/title context, and the record's finding should state the visible anchor.
- The page should make its side-appropriate source role visible. For `company_update_or_capability_claim`, it should be a company-controlled product, case, release, filing, investor, blog, or capability page tied to the case. For `external_deployment_or_counterparty_anchor`, it should be a customer, operator, integrator, supplier, counterparty, acquirer, exchange/filing, or comparable external source that names a customer/operator/site/facility/region/counterparty or real operational context; reputable trade coverage is acceptable only when it names that anchor. For `operational_or_software_substance`, it should expose concrete physical automation or software substance involved in the case, such as robot count, throughput, facility/site count, SKU/bin scale, workflow step, goods-to-person/AMR/AS/RS/sortation/picking/palletizing/storage function, WES/WMS integration, fleet/task orchestration, optimization, APIs, simulation, AI/control, or comparable detail. For `independent_outcome_or_scale_validation`, it should be a source not controlled by the studied company that independently validates an outcome, scale, live-use status, productivity, accuracy, training-time, fleet/site/throughput count, contract or purchase status, rollout state, or another measurable deployment result for the same case. Generic "uses robots", "uses automation", "improves efficiency", "trusted partner", or "solution leader" language is not enough without a concrete mechanism, status, scale, or measured result.
- The page should expose a concrete side-specific finding for the same case. Generic homepages, vendor lists, market reports, logo walls, and broad "automation leader" language do not count unless the page itself carries the case-specific side evidence.
- For each (`company`, `case_name`) case, try to use at least three distinct root domains across the four evidence sides. Do not reuse one URL for all four sides. The independent validation side must come from a source family outside the studied company's controlled pages, and should normally be different from the company-update source; it may share an external/customer page only when that page independently states the validation outcome or scale detail. A page can satisfy more than one side only when it independently carries the side role and concrete side finding; otherwise find a separate source.
